    "text": "I would like to introduce my wife, Hermina-- my wife, my love, my life for 49 years. We have met practically right after liberation in 1945. We married in 1946, like three or four months, five months after we wrote our engagement, Orthodox engagement. And we have met in an attic. [LAUGHS] But we had a very good life together. And it's just too bad that our parents were not with us to see how happy we had lived our life here. This is a picture of my father and mother. My father had perished, had died three days after liberation in, in Dachau. My mother was taken to Chelmno. And she was-- she perished in Chelmno, toge-- together with my brother. My, my father's name is Hersh Piernikarz. My mother's name is Rochma Piernikarz. Her maiden name is Frant. These pictures were-- this picture was made from two separate pictures when my mother was much younger. And she-- they weren't even married. But I got my father's picture from Argentina-- my mother's picture from Argentina and my father's picture from Belgium. This is the house that we lived in with my father and mother and my brother, Loeser. This is in the town of Lask. And this street was [? Bershaska ?] number two. We lived downstairs. And the way I was told, this is the house where I wa-- I was born in. And upstairs on the upper floor, my father had his factory, where he was making men's clothing. This is the inside of a house that we lived in. And the window on the right hand side where the men are standing, this is the windows that my mother used to hand out the food on [? Sukkot. ?] Because there was a [? Sukkot ?] built right into that window. And this is the way my mother on [? Sukkot ?] would just hand out the food for us to enjoy [? Sukkot. ?] In this picture, we see what used to be our synagogue. And now, the Poles are using it for a firehouse. Outside of the synagogue, there was a graveyard that is now about 550 years old. And in, and [? instead ?] living to leave the people rest in peace, the Poles have made a parking lot out of this cemetery. To the right of the synagogue, there is the ritual bed called the mikvah. And at the upper floor in that mikvah, we had our cheder for many years, where we learned Hebrew. At this picture, I'm 19 years old. It was 1945 in September, and taken in Poland when I went to get my aunt. This is my ID picture from the displaced persons police in [? Lasberg, ?] where I was a sergeant of the police for a number of years. On this picture, I'm with my wife. We were married at that time. It was in 1946, in April. This is our oldest son, Harry Pierson. He is a professor in a university. He's got a PhD in math. He's a wonderful son and a wonderful father to his children. This is our youngest son, Norman, with his wife, Joanne, Matthew, our grandson Matthew, and our granddaughter, Jennifer. They're beautiful, wonderful people. And we're very proud of them, every one of them. And this picture, in addition to my wife and our oldest son Harry, are our grandchildren and our niece, Sarah. This is a picture of the monument in Chelmno, where my mother and my brother have perished. And on the monument, the right side, it says in Polish, we remember. And we definitely do. This is the back of the monument, where it is written that the, the victims are crying out for our future brothers never to forget what happened, what the Nazis did to them. And those that saw what was happening, to tell the world about it. They should-- the world should never forget what happened here. This is our wedding picture where we didn't have anything in the world and anyone, just the two of us. And we started to build a family. And this is our picture 49 years later, where we have built a family in spite of what the Nazis wanted to do to us. But we still do-- still miss those dear, dear to us that didn't see our joy of bringing up a new family.",
